Modeling multiple variables

library(MASS)
library(ggplot2)
boston <- Boston
ggplot(boston, aes(x = tax, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = dis, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = age, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = ptratio, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = black, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = lstat, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = rm, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = nox, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = indus, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = zn, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(boston, aes(x = crim, y = medv)) +
  geom_point()

X <- model.matrix(model)
dim(X)
## [1] 506   5
betahat <- solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) %*% Boston$medv
betahat
##                   [,1]
## (Intercept) 24.4713576
## rm           4.2237922
## ptratio     -0.9736458
## lstat       -0.6654360
## dis         -0.5519263
sig <- summary(model)$sigma
varCovMatrix <- sig ^ 2 * solve(t(X) %*% X)
dim(t(X) %*% X)
## [1] 5 5

\[\begin{equation} CI_{1-\alpha} = [\hat\beta_{1} - t_{1 - \alpha / 2 ; n - p} * SE(\hat\beta_1), \hat\beta_1 + t_{1 - \alpha / 2 ; n - p} * SE(\hat\beta_1)] \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} CI_.95(\hat\beta_1) = [-.66544 - t_{1 - .05 / 2 ; 501} * .04675, -.66544 + t_{1 - .05 / 2 ; 501} * .04675] \end{equation}\] 
betahat[2] + c(-1, 1) * qt(.975, 501) * se[2]
